The paper deals with regular languages and finite automata, which are topics typically studied in the formal language theory (cs.FL) sub-category. The focus on transition complexity suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category, as transition functions are a key component of automata and related data structures. The paper's exploration of Boolean operations on regular languages may also make it relevant to the logic in computer science (cs.LO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper's analysis of the differences between transition complexity and state complexity may be of interest to researchers in the computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of information theory concepts such as entropy may make it relevant to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
